clautolisp-windows-pathname-mapping — a path/pathname mapping layer for cross-environment Windows
=================================================================================================

Reported from: pathname-resolution problems surfaced while loading
cadaptor under clautolisp (relative paths, cwd/PWD), generalised to
the underlying Windows portability problem.
Observed on: design issue; concrete symptoms on clautolisp 1.2.7 /
alfe 1.1.16. Primary target: MS-Windows builds/runs.

Terminology
-----------

- pathname : the Common Lisp notion (structured object).
- path     : the POSIX / AutoCAD / BricsCAD notion (a plain string).

The AutoLISP/AutoCAD/BricsCAD API works with PATH STRINGS, so
clautolisp must be compatible with them; it cannot expose CL
pathnames to user code.

Summary
-------

There is a fundamental problem mapping CL pathnames to physical paths.

On macOS and Linux, CL implementations are well-behaved: the mapping
from pathnames to paths is handled correctly, roots are unambiguous
("/"), and a single environment is in play.

On MS-Windows there is NOT a single environment. Several coexisting
environments use different path syntaxes and different virtual mount
points / roots for the same physical files:

- Native Windows: drive-letter roots, e.g. `C:/...`.
- Cygwin / MSYS2: POSIX-style roots; `C:/` appears as `/c/` or
  `/mnt/c` (the latter under WSL).
- From native Windows, an MSYS2 `/` is actually something like
  `C:/msys64/`.
- `~/` (home) resolves to a variety of paths depending on the
  environment.

Worse:

- A program such as SBCL may have been COMPILED in one environment
  (msys2, WSL, native) and RUN in another. WSL is especially nasty
  because it presents itself as Linux (`uname` says Linux) while the
  surrounding Windows paths still exist.
- The environment clautolisp was COMPILED in can differ from the
  environment it is RUN in, which can differ again from the syntax of
  the paths the USER passes to it.

So at runtime there are (at least) three frames of reference to
reconcile:

1. what the CL implementation expects as physical pathnames — syntax
   and roots / mount points — i.e. essentially the environment SBCL
   (or the host CL) was compiled in;
2. what the run-time environment expects (which Windows environment we
   are actually running under);
3. the paths the user gives us (in yet another syntax/rooting).

Expected
--------

clautolisp needs a path-mapping layer (conceptually similar to
logical pathnames) that:

- knows frame (1): the physical-pathname syntax and roots the
  underlying CL implementation was built for;
- knows frame (2): the path syntax and mount points of the runtime
  environment;
- can transform / map paths between (3) the user-supplied syntax and
  whatever the CL runtime actually needs to hit the right physical
  file.

Constraints / notes
-------------------

- We cannot "just use CL logical pathnames": the AutoLISP/AutoCAD/
  BricsCAD API passes plain path strings, and user code expects path
  strings back. The mapping must be compatible with that string-based
  API and be transparent to user code.
- Exposing CL logical pathnames as a *clautolisp extension* (opt-in,
  on top of the string API) is a separate idea worth considering, but
  it does not replace the mapping layer above.
- macOS/Linux can keep the trivial identity mapping; the layer only
  needs to do real work on Windows / cross-environment builds.

Why it matters
--------------

Without this, clautolisp on Windows will mis-resolve user paths
whenever the compile-time and run-time environments disagree (a very
common situation: SBCL from msys2/WSL, run under native Windows or
vice-versa). Path strings that work in one frame silently fail or hit
the wrong file in another.

Suggested direction
-------------------

- Detect, at build time, the physical-pathname syntax/roots the host
  CL expects (record it in the image).
- Detect, at run time, the active Windows environment (native /
  Cygwin / MSYS2 / WSL) and its mount-point mapping.
- Implement a canonicalisation/translation step applied to every path
  string crossing the API boundary (in: user/AutoLISP -> CL; out: CL
  -> user/AutoLISP), driven by the (build-env, run-env) pair.
- Add a conformance test matrix across the environment combinations.

Related
-------

- clautolisp-boot-cwd-pwd-pathname-defaults.issue (cwd/PWD at boot —
  a special case of getting the base reference right).
- cad-path-dotdot-resolution.issue (`..` semantics once the base and
  rooting are correct).

Triage (clautolisp 1.2.10)
--------------------------

DEFERRED — kept open. This is a cross-environment design issue, not a
bounded bug: it requires a path-mapping layer driven by the
(build-env, run-env) pair, plus a conformance matrix across native
Windows / Cygwin / MSYS2 / WSL. None of that is reproducible or
testable on the Linux/macOS build hosts, so it cannot be implemented
and verified here.

The narrow, testable subset it shares with cadaptor's symptoms —
relative paths resolving against the live cwd at boot — was the
separable bug and is fixed in 1.2.8 (see
clautolisp-boot-cwd-pwd-pathname-defaults.issue). On macOS/Linux the
mapping is the identity, so that fix is sufficient there; the Windows
mapping layer remains future design work, to be scheduled against a
real Windows target.
